definition.value: The open-chain aldehyhde form of L-arabinose.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine having palmitoyl and glutaroyl groups at positions 1 and 2 respectively.
A melibiose that has beta-configuration at the anomeric hydroxy group.
An L-cysteine thioether that is L-cysteine in which the hydrogen of the thiol group is substituted by a 2,3-bis(palmitoyloxy)propyl group.
Any ester of L-cysteine.
A phytofluene having (E)-double bonds at the 6-, 12-, 14-, 18-, 22- and 26 positions and (Z)-double bonds at the 10- and 16-positions.
A trisaccharide comprised of three D-glucose residues connected by alpha(1->4) linkages.
A maltotriose trisaccharide in which the glucose residue at the reducing end is in the aldehydo open-chain form.
A lipid-rich mixture containing glycerol, fatty acids, phosphoric acid and other components.
A member of the class of uridines that is uridine in which the hydrogen at position 5 of the pyrimidine ring is substituted by a 2-amino-2-oxoethyl group.
Zwitterionic form of a polar amino acid having an anionic carboxy group and a protonated amino group.
A butanediol in which hydroxylation is at C-2 and C-3.
An N-acylneuraminic acid in which the acyl substituent on nitrogen is glycolyl and which has beta-configuration at the anomeric centre.
A methyl glycoside that is beta-D-galactopyranosyl-(1->4)-2-acetamido-2-deoxy-beta-D-glucopyranose in which the anomeric hydroxy group is replaced by methoxy.
A methyl glycoside that is beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-beta-D-GlcNAc-(1->3)-beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-D-GlcNAc in which the anomeric hydroxy group is replaced by a beta-methoxy.
A methyl glycoside derived from a hexasaccharide consisting of three units N-acetyllactosamine coupled in a linear sequence by beta-(1->3') linkages.
Any mannosamine carrying an N-acetyl substituent
An N-acetyl-D-mannosamine 6-phosphate having alpha-configuration at the anomeric centre.
An N-acyl-D-mannosamine 6-phosphate having the N-acyl specified as acetyl.
An N-acyl-D-mannosamine phosphate having the phosphate group placed at the 6-position.
Any mannosamine phosphate having D-configuration and carrying an N-acyl substituent.
A carbohydrate acid derivative anion arising from deprotonation of one or more oxoacid OH groups of any polysaccharide acid.
An S-farnesyl-L-cysteine where the C=C double bonds at the 2- and 6-positions both have (E)-configuration.
A monomethylxanthine having the methyl group located at the 3-position. It is a metabolite of caffeine.
A methylxanthine carrying a single methyl substituent at any position.
A 3-methylxanthine tautomer where the imidazole proton is located at the 9-position.
A 3-methylxanthine tautomer where the imidazole proton is located at the 7-position.
An N-acylneuraminic acid in which the acyl substituent on nitrogen is glycoloyl and which has alpha-configuration at the anomeric centre.
A methyl glycoside that is beta-D-galactopyranosyl-(1->4)-2-acetamido-2-deoxy-alpha-D-glucopyranose in which the anomeric hydroxy group is replaced by methoxy.
A (1->3)-beta-D-glucan consisting of 15 glucosyl residues linked in a linear sequence.
Any lyxose having D-configuration.
A beta-D-glucan consisting of [3)-beta-D-Glcp-(1->]15 in which the fifth and tenth glucosides from the reducing end are substituted at position 6 by beta-D-glucoside residues.
Any lyxose having L-configuration.
An L-lyxose in cyclic pyranose form.
The D-enantiomer of mannosamine.
A D-mannosamine in cyclic pyranose form.
Any rhamnose having L-configuration. L-rhamnose occurs naturally in many plant glycosides and some gram-negative bacterial lipopolysaccharides.
An L-rhamnose in cyclic pyranose form.
The methyl glycoside of the disaccharide beta-D-galactofuranosyl-(1->6)-alpha-D-mannose.
The methyl glycoside of the disaccharide beta-D-galactofuranosyl-(1->3)-alpha-D-mannose.
An acyclic carotene having the structure of psi,psi-carotene shortened by the formal removal of a prenyl group from each end of the molecule.
An acyclic carotene having the structure 7',8'-dihydro-psi,psi-carotene with cis-double bonds at C-7, C-9 and C-9'.
An acyclic psi,psi-carotene having cis double bonds at C-7, -7', -9 and -9'.
An acyclic carotene having the structure of lycopene with two hydrogen atoms abstracted from the C(3)-C(4) bond to form an extra trans double bond.
The carotenone that is the 2-oxo derivative of (3E)-1-methoxy-3,4-didehydro-1,2,7',8'-tetrahydro-psi,psi-carotene.
A carotenol having the structure of rhodopin with two hydrogen atoms abstracted from the C(3)-C(4) bond to form an extra trans double bond.
Any branched-chain fatty acid containing methyl branches only.
The carotenol formed by demethylation of the carotenoid ether spheroidene.
A tricarboxylic acid trianion resulting from the removal of a proton from each of the carboxy groups of tricarballylic acid.
The indol-3-yl carboxylic acid anion formed by loss of a proton from the carboxy group of (5-hydroxyindol-3-yl)acetic acid; principal microspecies at pH 7.3
